title: For Sale:  1945 Production Remington Rand 1911 A1 Marked United States Property U.S. Army
location: Toledo,  Oregon Coast, Oregon Coast, Oregon
postcontent:
Hi everyone. My father is in stage 4 cancer and has now lost his life insurance. To help out my step mother I am now forced to sell some of his guns for him. This pistol was produced in late 1945 and is one of the very last ones. If you know the history of these then you know that the RR are considered the very best of all 1911 A1s produced with the quality second to none. A quick Google search will tell you all you need to know about this. 
All markings are there and are correct. Several decades ago the slide stop was polished as this seemed to be a bit of a fad back then. The pistol retains much of the original finish but has been taken down at some point in time to where you can actually see the milling marks on the slide. Collectors may or may not like this but this is still a very valuable and highly sought after pistol. The weapon functions and performs as it should. I have the two era correct mags that came with this when it was purchased used about 40 years ago. One is stamped with the letter G on the floor plate as well as the number 23. The second one is not stamped anywhere that I can see. The pistol is marked with a number 10 in yellow paint on the bottom of the frame. All other markings are correct and can be seen although I have to use a magnifying glass and light as I have had a series of small strokes and can no longer see this tiny stuff. I did take it to a respected gun smith for verification of all the markings. You are certainly welcome to inspect this for yourself. The grips are obviously the rubber finger grove type by Hogue but my father does have the original ones somewhere. I do not know how long it will take my to find them so the pistol will be sold as is for now. If I find the originals I am willing to mail them to the buyer. 
Now, the important part. Price. We all know the approximate values of theses somewhat rare pistols. I am going to leave this open for now and look at realistic offers. My father does not have much time and is looking for cash for all of his firearms to help my step mother with the massive medical bills that are already nearing 200k. That being said, I have been buying and selling guns for about 35 years and am willing to look at trades for guns that I can sell and then give the money to my step mother. Expensive guns are fairly hard to sell here at the coast where I live so multiple guns in trade would actually work out better for us at this point. 
As for a price, I will say that I have taken this pistol to a couple of different shops, we only have two here, and the lowball offer from one of them was 1000 dollars which is not going to happen. The gun will stay with me and go to one of my kids when the time comes before I will sell it for 1000 dollars. That being said, please feel free to toss out some offers of cash, trade or some of each. I live in Toledo and my father lives over in Brownsville. I am willing to travel between here and there for a deal but lets be realistic here. I am not going to run all over hell and back for a bunch of tire kickers who want this for nothing. Please excuse me if this sounds rude but I have been down that road before and simply do not have time for games under the circumstances that I mentioned about my fathers timeline. Our family is hoping and praying for more time but the cancer is now in his femurs and hips as well as his prostate, colon, lower intestine and skin so every day is a crap shoot. He has gone from walking 5 miles a day to a walker and now to a wheelchair in less than one month due to the cancer now being labeled as super aggressive. Please excuse the sob story but I want to explain the urgency to sell these guns. If I had time I would simply place it for sale on Gunbrokers.
Thank you for your time and I look forward to hearing from you.

*******Remington Rand is not on the drop down list so I chose Remington but the pistol is a genuine Remington Rand******

My name is Mike and you can reach me via email, phone or text. My cell number is REDACTED

title: For Sale:  Custom Swiss K-31 Scout
postcontent: Up for sale is a one of a kind, custom built Swiss K-31 straight-pull bolt action carbine. I Purchased this rifle for $300, specifically to build a scout rifle out of. It is chambered in 7.5x55 Swiss, and the ammo is readily available online, and isn't too expensive. Soft nose hunting rounds are also available. I started this build with a scope mount i found online, that replaces the rear sight. I matched that with a $300 Nikon Force XR long-eye relief scope with BDC. I had a gunsmith cut the barrel at 16 5/8", and threaded 5/8x24 and put a Troy Claymore muzzle break on the barrel. After that came the Boyd's Gun Stocks monte carlo stock in Pepper. It took me awhile to get the gun to fit properly, but it fits like a charm and feels wonderful. I finished the stock with a rub on polyurethane finish, about 9 coats worth. It shines like a new penny and feels great. Gun shoots great, i was getting about 1" groups at 100 yards off of a good rest, and I've never considered myself that great of a shot. Gun is a 1958 model, and numbers match. I have the name and address of the Swiss citizen it was issued to, on a card I found under the butt plate. Gun will come with 60 Rounds of Swiss FMJ ammo. Thanks for looking, no Trades. $600 is the price.

title: For Sale/Trade:  1933 Izhevsk Mosin Nagant 91/30 w/ sling, bayonet, and 100 rounds of ammo
postcontent:
Wanting to sell a 1933 Izhevsk Mosin Nagant 91/30.  It's in excellent condition with dark, deep grooves in the rifling, no cracks or serious blemishes in the stock other than some dents and dings, and matching serials on the bolt, hex receiver, and baseplate.  Bolt is smooth and easy to work.
Marks on the barrel are a Soviet Union Red Army emblem, two circle K marks suggesting it's been sighted twice, three circle tombstone marks suggesting it's been black powder tested, and a small Cyrillic marking on the barrel shank I have no idea about because I don't read Cyrillic moon speak scribbles.
Sights are standard WW2 Soviet Mosin Nagant hooded front sights with 2000 meter rear adjustable sights.
Bluing of the metal is almost perfect.
Includes WW2 era Red Army dog-collared sling and bayonet.  The bayonet is old, but the serial number and all markings have faded and the exact origin is unknown.  Probably Russian.  Attaches and detaches without problem and is quite sharp and doubles as a disassembly tool.
Tested on the range and works excellently and without issue.  Overall an excellent gun in a country where Mosins in great condition are becoming rare and expensive
I will include all my 7.62mmx54r ammunition with it.  It's a mix of Soviet surplus and Monarch (Academy sport's brand).  Roughly 100 rounds.  I need to recount.  If less I'll buy more.
Contact me for pictures of everything.  Will include timestamp if desired.  I'm an individual with a thing for antique guns, not a shop, and am open to negotiation.
